\begin_layout Subsection
Bonding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the reactor is made in the clean room and the wanted catalyst to be
 tested is deposited in the reactor volume, the sample of course needs to
 be sealed to form a complete reactor.
 This is done through the process of anodic bonding, which is thoroughly
 described in earlier theses from the group and will only very briefly describe
 it here.
 The point in anodic bonding is to hermeticly seal a pyrex lid to a silicon
 wafer which is done by applying a high potential to the lid compared to
 the silicon and heat the structure to a temperature where the pyrex becomes
 ionically conductiong, which happens around 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

280
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}$
\end_inset

C.
 In this configuration ions from the lid will be transported to the wafer
 and at the same time forming strong chemical bonds that seals the lid to
 the wafer.
 Once the bonding is complete it will be so strong that the interface will
 not be any weaker than the rest of the reactor structure.
 Unfortunately no method of reversing the process is known and thus the
 lid cannot be removed from the sample, once the bonding is performed.
 In the microreactors, we often deposit samples that we do not want to heat,
 especially not in air, and for that reason, we often use a so called cold-bondi
ng method, which was developed here at CINF
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Vesborg2010"

\end_inset

.
 When cold bonding, the reactor is carefully positioned on top of a cold-finger
 which will keep the reactor area at temperatures close to room temperature
 while the rest of the sample is heated and thus protects the sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
General measurement principle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course in order to do actual measurements, one needs more than just a
 bonded silicon reactor.
 To be able to do actual measurements it is neseccary to have som kind of
 gas-handling, a way of heating the reactor, as well as a detection mechanism
 for the reactant and products.
 As pretty much the rest of this thesis will discuss, this can be implemented
 in many specific ways, but the overall concept is vey general and should
 be introduced before moving on to the details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reaction gases are supplied to the two inlets by flow controllers capable
 of controlling the gas flow in various range, typically on the order 0-10
 mL/min.
 The flow controllers have an analog interface which allows the flow to
 be set by a 0--5
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

V voltage and the actual output is returned also in the form of a 0--5
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

V signal, this makes it very easy to interface the flow controllers with
 standard DAQ-cards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The capillary flow is fed into a quadropole mass-spectrometer (QMS) for
 analysis while any surplus of gas from the inlets is passed directly through
 to the outlet via a pressure controller allowing control of reactor pressure.
 The design makes sure that all gases exposed to the catalyst under investigatio
n are measured by the QMS ensuring an extremely high sensitivity of the
 system.
 
